compactification~\cite{NSS}. We will find this behavior in other cases.

We have also examined other internal spaces, but without any adjustable
parameter we find that neither flat nor spherical spaces give accelerating
cosmologies~\cite{NO1}.


\section{SM2-brane}

The SM2-brane in M-theory can be obtained from (\ref{oursol}) by putting
$p=q+1=3, \epsilon=+1, a=0, c_\phi=0$ without dilaton and $\Delta =3(n-1)$.
We also put $c\equiv c_1=c_2=c_3, c'\equiv c_1'=c_2'=c_3'$ and then
$\beta=\frac{1}{n-1}\sqrt{\frac{3(n+2)}{n}}\; c$ is determined from (\ref{condconst}).
The solution~(\ref{oursol}) then gives
\begin{eqnarray}
ds_d^2 &=& [\cosh 3c(t-t_2)]^{2/(n-1)} \Bigg[ -e^{2ng(t)-6c'/(n-1)} dt^2
+ e^{2g(t)-6c'/(n-1)}d\Sigma_{n,\sigma}^2 \nonumber\\
&& \hspace{20 mm} +\; [\cosh 3c(t-t_2)]^{- 2(n+2)/3(n-1)2c_\alpha'} d{\bf x}^2\Bigg].
\end{eqnarray}
This is the universe~(\ref{dsol})-(\ref{4sol}) with
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta(t) &=& [\cosh3c(t-t_2)]^{1/(n-1)} e^{g(t) -3c'/(n-1)}, \nonumber\\
S(t) &=& [\cosh3c(t-t_2)]^{(n+2)/6(n-1)} e^{ng(t)/2 -(n+2)c'/2(n-1)}.
\label{mfactor}
\end{eqnarray}
We now discuss three internal spaces~(\ref{ints}) separately.


\subsection{Hyperbolic internal space}

The conditions~(\ref{cond1}) and (\ref{cond2}) for $n=7$ of our interest and
hyperbolic internal space $\sigma=-1$ are (again shifting the time to set $t_1=0$)
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{cond11}
&& n_2(t) \equiv \frac{3}{4} \tanh[3c(t-t_2)]-\frac{\sqrt{21}}{4}
\coth(3\sqrt{3/7}ct)>0, \\
&& \frac{9}{8}\left(\frac{1}{\cosh^2[3c(t-t_2)]}
+ \frac{1}{\sinh^2(3\sqrt{3/7}ct)}\right) - n_2^2(t) > 0.
\label{cond12}
\end{eqnarray}

Here we can again consider that our universe evolves only for $t<0$.
The left hand side of these eqs. for $c=1$ and $t_2=0$ are shown in
Fig.~\ref{f4}, and the behavior of the scale factor $S(t)$ in~(\ref{mfactor}) is
depicted in Fig.~\ref{f5}. We again see that there is a certain period of
negative time that these conditions are satisfied~\cite{NO1}.
