\section{SD2-brane}

In this section, we discuss accelerating cosmologies from SD2-brane.

\subsection{SD2-brane obtained from SM2-brane}

We first show how the SD2-brane can be obtained by dimensional reduction
from SM2-branes. Though it is possible to examine general dimensions,
we restrict ourselves to $d=11$ here. We will see why the qualitative
behavior is similar to SM2-brane.

The 10-dimensional metric in the string frame is obtained from the
11-dimensional one by the relation
\begin{eqnarray}
ds_{11}^2 = e^{-2\phi/3} ds_{10,s}^2 + e^{4\phi/3} dx_{10}^2.
\label{11metric}
\end{eqnarray}
In our solutions~(\ref{oursol}), we consider SM2-brane by taking $q=2$,
but we set $p=4$ with one extra coordinate outside SM2-brane, in which
direction we make dimensional reduction. We choose $x_1,x_2,x_3$ to be
the SD2-brane world-volume and $x_4$ the direction of dimensional reduction.
We further set $c\equiv c_1=c_2=c_3, c' \equiv c_1'=c_2'=c_3'$ but leave
$c_4$ and $c_4'$ arbitrary. There is no dilaton which comes from the metric
as~(\ref{11metric}) upon dimensional reduction, and we put $a=c_\phi=0$.
This gives
\begin{eqnarray}
\phi &=& \frac{1}{4} \ln [\cosh 3c (t-t_2)] + \frac{3}{4} (c+2c_4)t
+ \frac{3}{2} c'_4, \nonumber\\
ds_{10,s}^2 &=& e^{2\phi/3} [\cosh 3c (t-t_2)]^{1/3}\Bigg[
e^{-(c+2c_4)t/5 - 2(3c'+c_4')/5} \left\{ - e^{12 g(t)} dt^2
+ e^{2g(t)}d\Sigma_{6,\sigma}^2\right\} \nonumber\\
&& \hspace{20 mm} +\; [\cosh 3c(t-t_2)]^{-1} e^{2c'} d{\bf x}^2 \Bigg].
\end{eqnarray}
In the Einstein frame $ds_{10,E}^2 = e^{-\phi/2} ds_{10,s}^2$, this reduces to
\begin{eqnarray}
ds_{10,E}^2 &=& [\cosh 3c (t-t_2)]^{3/8}\Bigg[ e^{-3(c+2c_4)t/40-3(8c'
+c_4')/20} \left\{ - e^{12 g(t)} dt^2 + e^{2g(t)}d\Sigma_{6,\sigma}^2
\right\} \nonumber\\
&& \hspace{20 mm} +\; [\cosh 3c(t-t_2)]^{-1} e^{(c+2c_4)t/8+(8c'+c_4')/4} d{\bf x}^2
\Bigg].
\end{eqnarray}
The relation to the notation of \cite{CGG} is given by
\begin{eqnarray}
c=\frac{16}{15} \alpha, \quad
c_4=\frac{5}{8} c_1 -\frac{8}{15}\alpha,
\end{eqnarray}
which must obey (\ref{condconst}) or
\begin{eqnarray}
30 \beta^2 = \frac{128}{25}\alpha^2 + \frac{15}{32} c_1^2.
\end{eqnarray}

The scale factor $S(t)$ and $\delta(t)$ are given as
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{dfactor}
\delta(t) &=& [\cosh (16\alpha/5)(t-t_2)]^{3/16} e^{g(t) -3c_1t/64 - 3\tilde c'/4},\nonumber\\
S(t) &=& [\cosh (16\alpha/5)(t-t_2)]^{1/4} e^{3g(t) -c_1 t/16 - \tilde c'},\\
\phi &=& \frac{1}{4}\ln[\cosh(16\alpha/5)(t-t_2)] +\frac{15}{16}c_1 t +c_\phi',
\nonumber
\end{eqnarray}
where we have also put
\begin{eqnarray}
\tilde c'= \frac{8c'+c_4'}{10}, \quad
c_\phi' = \frac{3}{2} c_4'.
\end{eqnarray}
On the other hand, if we consider the SD2-brane with $d=10, q=2, p=3, n=6,
a=\frac{1}{2},\epsilon=+1$ in eq.~(\ref{oursol}), we get precisely (\ref{dfactor})
with different parametrization
\begin{eqnarray}
c=\alpha + \frac{5}{64}c_1, \quad
c_\phi = \frac{15}{16}c_1 - \frac{4}{5}\alpha, \quad
c' = \frac{5}{4} \tilde c'.
\end{eqnarray}
The scale factors~(\ref{dfactor}) almost coincide with those for SM2-brane
in~(\ref{mfactor}) if we choose $n=6$, though the power of the $\cosh$ is
slightly different and there is an additional $c_1 t$ term in the
exponent. However, the difference is small and one may expect
that qualitative features remain the same. This is the reason why one finds
basically the same behavior as SM2-brane. To confirm this, we present
some results for SD2-brane below.

Continuing this reduction, one should leave the constants $c_\alpha$ arbitrary
in order to get general lower-dimensional solutions;
in the SM2-brane solution of ref.~\cite{CGG}, homogeneity of the space
outside the S-brane is assumed, and then general solutions cannot be
obtained by dimensional reduction. If we start with our solutions without
putting any relations among $c_\alpha$'s, we can simultaneously discuss
all possible cases. This is another virtue of our solutions, in addition
to the fact that they cover the vacuum solution.


\subsection{Hyperbolic internal space}

The conditions~(\ref{cond1}) and (\ref{cond2}) give
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{cond41}
&& n_5(t) \equiv \frac{4}{5}\alpha \tanh[(16\alpha/5)(t-t_2)] - 3\beta \coth(5\beta t)
-\frac{c_1}{16} >0, \\
&& \frac{32\alpha^2/25}{\cosh^2[(16\alpha/5)(t-t_2)]}
+ \frac{15\beta^2/2}{\sinh^2(5\beta t)} - n_5^2(t) > 0,
\label{cond42}
\end{eqnarray}
where we have again set $t_1=0$ by a shift of time.

The conditions~(\ref{cond41}) and (\ref{cond42}) for $\alpha=0.92, c_1=1,\beta=\frac{2}{5}$
was examined in \cite{R}, and the qualitative behavior is found to be the
same as SM2-brane, as expected. We have studied how the behavior changes
if we change parameter $t_2$. The results for $t_2=-1,+1$ are shown
in Figs.~\ref{f14} and \ref{f15}, respectively.
